The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic since this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing – a virtual operator that obligates traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
Since the Czech operators belong to the most dear ones in Europe, we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
Finally, ČTú confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of mobile operators in the Czech Republic SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and high coverage over 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile telephony operators like to lag behind the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTú) , Pavel Dvořák , who has once expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his network has probably no more possibilities. (For the rest it might be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to ours were echoed in Britain.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that they can really succeed.
Finally, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which the Czech Republic belongs among others U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete task force.
In order to actually function, it is enough for many less customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the most restricted services offer
So for example Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers texts that cost at least half compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move, even the bet on a group-brick not recently.
This operator points to so specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust" says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be said by us as in Poland.
It doubts the press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, services are relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic, no possibilities, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not have much expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will happen rather in other countries in our area," said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not very favourable to this view.
Rather, they are trying to do everything because they do not create any potential competitors.
For a while he has not hidden his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would thus like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the business customer field.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first you get better is.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefónika O2.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The press spokesman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we must have had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates his attention rather than reaching his applications for the 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile telephony operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus lower profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The discomforts around creation U:fon testify that when operators hold to something they know how to bind on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure against ČTú during the creation period of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This bears witness to the public access information from the ČTú websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has been little boosted further with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would bring about him and above all his high services.
However, the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising the total lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of ČTú that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, has taken up its typical position with regard to the whole problem.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, the Section for External Relations UOHS, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
On the other hand, the office which has to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators work commonly, we can see that their market entry has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But, of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence, is left alone.
The same as the same price of petrol for all petrol is certainly the fruit of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he has no corresponding responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by ČTú, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the accounts logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators do in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time the complaints from the stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during the negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Download responsibility to ČTú in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which UOHS keeps itself out of the way.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, ČTú's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications were not promoted until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected to improve the situation.
That is what UOHS representatives need to know more than good, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one looks
While we are not aware of this, the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone services prices which are only partially public.
These are usually the multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established persons.
The magic lies in the fact that the company against the operator appears as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sales.
"If the cases you're talking about, of which we're going to be interested, could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself from such an attitude at the same time.
From the activity of these companies there is a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile operators "
But this should be a bit strange to ČTú.
In addition there is another question for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has strong enough rights to reveal similar activities and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As the text has already been mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant decrease in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all the countries where the operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases the regulators intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him others agreed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are launching the whole case from one to the other like a boiling potato.
For our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more comfortable.
But we don't throw away the sponge.
If the information of the backstage is correct and the virtual operator will really appear from us soon, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on the bike.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly UOHS could remain improbable to the refusal (discrimination) of the others concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the day of recognition of the Czech State solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the hymn was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, choir step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national song one of the most beautiful inni.
Already before he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he has chosen specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and the choir, have the clear word, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divad it in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
He bought popularity and people spontaneously made it his.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
