Alcoholic receivers will have to install the "alcoholck"
The Ministry of Internal Affairs requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive alcohol in their blood, to install in their car the system which prevents driving the vehicle in a state of darkness or if it does not blow into the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney General of State, which will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the Attorney General's Office for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of the drivers reported more than once by driving in a state of darkness then return to driving the car.
The alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the air spiral and prevents the car from moving if the driver does not blow, or when a concentration of alcohol higher than the permitted one is detected.
The cost is more than EUR 1000 and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles with these devices allow to reduce up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is calculated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to stop these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And in order to facilitate their development, since the legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, without a doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the PSOE in which it is proposed to install this system on school buses, as has already been done in France.
