Some kids talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most it gets a scare, but actually it doesn't matter much.
This is a benign alternation of the so-called sleepwalk.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have said that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadicly (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in the month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (piping in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned, it can be associated with very high stages of fever, stress or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is not yet studied.
Also the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that happens the contrary (scream, shout, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be necessary to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. if combined with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to get too excited about the baby before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepilocks appear trying to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day they will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
