The encounter - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of her foundation yesterday, and her president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had all the reasons to rejoice, as the Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shocked by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was late to write a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of creating a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the years, we have regained the public's confidence," he explains before expressing pride that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, telling him that it has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely didn't know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
There was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports that when they have doubts and could achieve serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, blood was refused for those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, for some years, it has been shown that this disease is clearly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors to be directly recognized, rather than the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used up to that time were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, since the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be identified in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus greatly decreased.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400 000 to 500 000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV is found transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant", Dr. Décary continues before stressing that besides having safe resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Necessity increases as the population ages.
As the most aggressive cancer cures, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average make up only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
All healthy people who have reached 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of shortage are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today, life is so frenetic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, the Hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, and skin cells that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Québec who manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should begin to propose them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of taking cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access you", as the Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
