According to the result of a recent survey, the religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University performed an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God influences the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was performed with 12 Catholic believers and the same atheists, while everyone observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
