The intelligent machine imitates the flight of the scumbag
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if not to imitate the sensors of the obstacles in nature?
Like bees.
In the surprising project presented to CEATEC in Japan, the Calabrians gave the initial strategic direction to the Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo the Nissan built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized mini-auto with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system able to scan all collisions.
Flying the bees form a personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technology sector and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the ape, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers attracted the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the ape view.
The BR23C detects the obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the water, changes direction immediately by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
"If that weren't the robot car wouldn't react quickly to avoid collisions" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes a bee to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in an eyebrow.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and high energy density, which means that their duration is higher than lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantness of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot needs to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There's no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict to Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on serial vehicles.
Further possibility of application can be represented by unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leading to destination.
