What matters most, we need to raise awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to make them fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they originated.
"Scientists - the EU executive concludes - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and interested parties what measures might be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment".
At present, there is already a European security standard that limits to 100 dB the noise level of portable musical equipment, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these damage by using solutions such as reduction of levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week exceed the currently in force limits on the maximum permitted noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of the users of these devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
