Elelites in Danger
The phenomenon had already occurred a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
There is a confirmation from the New York Times of yesterday that the ongoing crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, instead conservative, hostile to "the Washington people" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and South states.
The soul, for the point, that became prepotently alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just mentioned, however, is just an example of the changes, of the great changes, that the current economic earthquake perhaps preanunciates or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps even here alone.
Both in the USA and in Europe the crisis seems to function as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these is the re-upgrading, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of State-Sovereignity in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of financial-banking institutions which, yes, have strong links with abroad, but first of all, are involved in the vast extent of the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In other words, the crisis appears economically worldwide, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of play or not to have much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies cannot decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the close it is only the States that own economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in sixth place.
They also have the necessary means and the right to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organization can possibly have in a similar way.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the state-of-the-art element is in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor that is very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, the increasingly sophisticated technology, the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalised finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized in a way that our future should, instead, be increasingly counting with those very little immaterial things that are the water, the harvest, the oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are nevertheless absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
So that those who are found to be sovereign, certainly possess several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without harvests, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, however, that overlooks a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, is so inadequate and full of shade areas.
And together something even deeper and in a certain disturbing sense: a discredit, a lack of indifference, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, it seems to be becoming more and more popular, in large sections of the population, to believe that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites as before, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall acceptance of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly foreign to the views of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "rives" electional or sudden developments of the collective moods of the last and most recent times, from the conservative assess in Austria-Baviera to the collapse of Labour Consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congresses against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
It has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their accredited newspapers, their intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and thus to represent, what is not from today taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, potentially stirring up.
In the face of all this talk of a 'rebellion of the masses' on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open for sure is not for nothing.
