When the energy is born from the waves now the bigs descend into the field
It is an extinct deposit, which occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now discovering it by the great global energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they put their eyes, and now they try to put their hands, big as the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmentalists and the new oil increase give impetus to the sector.
London's World Energy Council (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity requirement could be covered by sea-going motorcycle exploitation facilities.
This would be twice as much as the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would be currents and tides.
Colossi to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the understanding was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy are increasing and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying technologies on ocean energy - he has declared the spokesperson of a company associated with the giant oil tanker in the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal - and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the United States Committee on Energy, which is necessary to launch a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
It is a signal not long ago, especially if it is considered that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and President Bush has recently launched a plan for new trivellations.
In addition to Chevron there are the Verdant Power Inc. in New York and the Ocean Power in New Jersey to walk along the path of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, however unknown in the details, indicate to observers an upward interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about technology at the beginning, also because marine energy does not escape all the doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create big problems to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies must be used with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boe connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the boe up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floaters.
Pressure drives a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now, there are four installations of this type under design, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could serve for military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking using six submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement when there are tides spins the blades of turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said he has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorisations to take advantage of energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electricity, is currently worth the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that were like that of New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coast, they have already invested $7 million and a half in 2008 and planned investments up to 35 million for 2009.
